        <hl1>Wine Labels Good to the Touch</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <byline class="print_byline">By Elaine Louie</byline>
      <byline class="normalized_byline">Louie, Elaine</byline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Michel Chapoutier, a winemarker in France, and Herzog, California winemarker, both use labels in Braille; photo (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>An ocean away from each other, two men had the same idea: to design wine labels in Braille. Michel Chapoutier, a winemaker in France, started labeling bottles that way in 1994. Last year, Itamar Cohen, a graphic designer in Piermont, N.Y., designed a Braille label for Herzog wines in Santa Maria, Calif. The Herzog Cabernet is $25, and the M. Chapoutier Le Pavillon Ermitage is $200, at Park Avenue Liquor Shop, 292 Madison Avenue (41st Street).</p>
      </block>
